article.description: Rasheed Wallace scored nine of his 18 points down the stretch as the Portland Trail Blazers recorded a 90-84 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics.
article.headline: Sonics run out of gas in fourth quarter
article.linkText: Wallace scores 9 of his 18 in late going as Blazers stop Sonics
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Rasheed Wallace had a simple explanation for why the Portland Trail Blazers edged the Seattle SuperSonics.
Wallace

"We're just playing hard, man," Wallace said. "That's the bottom line, fellas." Wallace made two shots and two free throws in the final 2:16 as the Blazers beat the SuperSonics for the third time in as many game this season, 90-84 Wednesday night. "I thought he was the one that won the game for us, with his buckets down the stretch," Blazers coach Maurice Cheeks said. Wallace finished with 18 points, including nine in the final quarter, for Portland. Damon Stoudamire added 14, and Dale Davis had nine points and 13 rebounds for the Blazers. Portland didn't have any All-Stars this season, but Wallace, the team's leading scorer, is one in the eyes of his teammates. "Rasheed hit some big baskets for us and that's what an All-Star is all about, coming through in the clutch," Portland's Ruben Patterson said. "He was real big for us," Stoudamire said. "He made every big bucket that we needed. More importantly, he was asking for the ball down the stretch." The Sonics lost for the first time in four games since Vin Baker was sidelined with three dislocated toes on his left foot. Rashard Lewis scored 24 points for Seattle, which forced the Blazers to commit 17 turnovers. But the Sonics missed eight consecutive shots before Brent Barry converted an offensive rebound with 3.2 seconds to go. They ran out of gas in the fourth quarter of their fourth game in five days. "I don't want to say it's fatigue, but, yeah, that does play a part," Lewis said. "Brent and Gary both played 40 minutes last night and they were knocking down jump shots. That probably played a factor in not shooting the ball well tonight." The Sonics weren't surprised to see the Blazers call on Wallace in the clutch. Wallace took only nine shots all night, including two in the final quarter. "It's difficult to defend Wallace because he's so long," Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "Even if you sent a double team, he's able to pass over you and find open shooters. I thought we did a good job of mixing it up." Wallace made a 16-foot baseline jump shot over Lewis with 2:16 to go, sank a 10-foot bank shot with 22.9 seconds remaining and hit two free throws with 14.4 seconds left after being fouled by Desmond Mason. Gary Payton made a 3-pointer with 3:40 to go before Wallace tied it at 82 with two free throws. Rookie Vladimir Radmanovich had a chance to put Seattle back in front but missed two foul shots with 2:35 remaining. Wallace's 16-footer gave the Blazers an 84-82 lead. Lewis missed a 3-pointer with 1:26 left, and Mason missed a 12-footer 42 seconds later. Then Wallace hit his 10-footer and followed up with two free throws. With owner Paul Allen watching intently from his courtside seat, the Blazers got 12 points from Bonzi Wells, 11 from Patterson and 10 from Shawn Kemp. They outrebounded Seattle 49-39. In addition to his 24 points on 9-for-16 shooting, Lewis had six steals. Payton added 15 points and, Brent Barry and Mason each scored 12 points for the Sonics. Seattle shot 7-for-20 and scored 19 points in the fourth quarter.

Game notes
The Blazers beat the Sonics 113-92 in Portland on Dec. 8 and 92-86 in Seattle Jan. 29. ... Before the game, McMillan said he didn't know when he was going to get Baker back. Baker's left foot is in a boot. "He's out indefinitely," McMillan said. The Sonics are 10-4 without Baker this season. ... The Sonics lost rookie guard Earl Watson with 9:26 left when he got hit in the face accidentally by Patterson after he stealing the ball from Wallace under Portland's basket. Watson suffered a cut upper lip that required four stitches.
